…or create a new repository on the command line
echo "# project" >> README.md
git init
git add README.md
git commit -m "first commit"
git branch -M main
git remote add origin https://github.com/lppolletta/project.git
git push -u origin main
…or push an existing repository from the command line
git remote add origin https://github.com/lppolletta/project.git
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main

git checkout -b dev

Push the branch on github :
git push origin dev

When you want to commit something in your branch, be sure to be in your branch.

You can see all branches created by using :

git branch

Which will show :

approval_messages master master_clean Add a new remote for your branch :
git remote add https://github.com/lppolletta/project.git

Push changes from your commit into your branch :

git push origin https://github.com/lppolletta/project.git

Update your branch when the original branch from official repository has been updated :

git fetch [name_of_your_remote]

Then you need to apply to merge changes, if your branch is derivated from develop you need to do :

git merge [name_of_your_remote]/develop

Delete a branch on your local filesystem :

git branch -d [name_of_your_new_branch]

To force the deletion of local branch on your filesystem :

git branch -D [name_of_your_new_branch]

Delete the branch on github :

git push origin :[name_of_your_new_branch]